  </knowledge>

  <steps>
    <step order="1">Read `IOpenAiClient.cs` + `OpenAiClient.cs` to identify the structured-output / chat-completion methods + their typed-options patterns.</step>
    <step order="2">Read peer service examples (any existing classification or summarization service) for style alignment.</step>
    <step order="3">Define `IFileClassificationService` + `FileClassificationResult` record.</step>
    <step order="4">Implement `FileClassificationService`:
      - Constructor takes `IOpenAiClient`, `IOptions&lt;AiModelOptions&gt;` (or equivalent), `ILogger`
      - `ClassifyAsync` constructs a system prompt: "Classify this document into one of: NDA, patent, invoice, contract, lease, motion, other. Return JSON `{documentType, confidence}`."
      - User prompt truncated to first 4K chars of textContent (avoid full-doc cost for cheap classifier)
      - Calls gpt-4o-mini via `IOpenAiClient` with response-format=json
      - Parses + validates result (defensive: fallback to `{ documentType: "other", confidence: 0.0 }` on parse failure)
      - Logs fileId, sessionId, durationMs, resultDocumentType, confidence (tier-1 safe)</step>
    <step order="5">Author unit test stub in `tests/unit/Sprk.Bff.Api.Tests/Services/Ai/Sessions/FileClassificationServiceTests.cs` — mock `IOpenAiClient`; assert tier-1 logging + JSON parse + fallback path.</step>
    <step order="6">Run `dotnet build` + `dotnet test` for the new tests.</step>
    <step order="7">Measure BFF publish size.</step>
    <step order="8">code-review + adr-check (Step 9.5).</step>
    <step order="9">Update TASK-INDEX.md: 067 → ✅.</step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool name="Read">IOpenAiClient + peer services</tool>
    <tool name="Write">Service + interface + record + test stub</tool>
    <tool name="Bash">dotnet build / test / publish</tool>
